Master Regulator Analysis with RTN package

Pablo L. Cardozo

2024-07-04

This document describes the main coding steps used in this work to perform Master Regulator Analysis using the RTN package.

Downloading microglia transcriptomic data from ARCHS4

In this step, human microglia transcriptomic data is downloaded from ARCHS4 database and prepared for later co-expression network reconstruction using the human transcription factors as centroids.

setwd(/PATH/)

# Check if gene expression file was already downloaded, if not in current directory download file from repository

    print("Downloading compressed gene expression matrix.")
    download.file(url, destination_file, quiet = FALSE, mode = 'wb')
}

# Retrieve information from compressed data
samples = h5read(destination_file, "meta/samples/geo_accession")
genes = h5read(destination_file, "meta/genes/ensembl_gene_id")
series = h5read(destination_file, 'meta/samples/series_id')

# Identify columns to be extracted
sample_locations = which(samples %in% samp)

# extract gene expression from compressed data
expression = t(h5read(destination_file, "data/expression", index=list(sample_locations, 1:length(genes))))
H5close()
rownames(expression) = genes
colnames(expression) = samples[sample_locations]
series <- series[sample_locations]
batchid = match(series, unique(series))

# Remove low count genes
keep <- filterByExpr(expression, group = batchid)
expression <- expression[keep,]

# normalize samples and correct for differences in gene count distribution
correctedExpression <- ComBat_seq(expression, batchid, full_mod = F)
correctedExpression <- vst(correctedExpression)

# Print file
write.table(correctedExpression, file=extracted_expression_file, sep="\t", quote=FALSE, col.names=NA)
print(paste0("Expression file was created at ", getwd(), "/", extracted_expression_file))

# Creating data frame with gene annotations for network reconstruction

gene_annot <- as.data.frame(rownames(correctedExpression))
colnames(gene_annot) <- 'ENSEMBL'

db_homo_s <- useMart(biomart = 'ENSEMBL_MART_ENSEMBL', dataset = 'hsapiens_gene_ensembl')

dictionary <- getBM(attributes = c('ensembl_gene_id', 'hgnc_symbol', 'entrezgene_id'),
                    filters = 'ensembl_gene_id', values = gene_annot$ENSEMBL,
                    mart = db_homo_s, uniqueRows = F, useCache = T)

gene_annot <- left_join(gene_annot, dictionary, by = join_by('ENSEMBL' == 'ensembl_gene_id'),
                        multiple = 'first') %>% relocate(c(hgnc_symbol, entrezgene_id), .after = ENSEMBL)


gene_annot <- gene_annot[!is.na(gene_annot$hgnc_symbol),]
gene_annot <- gene_annot[gene_annot$hgnc_symbol != '',]

colnames(gene_annot) <- c('ENSEMBL', 'SYMBOL', 'ENTREZ')

write.table(gene_annot, file = 'gene_annotation.txt', quote = F, sep = '\t')

Reconstructing co-expression network around transcription factors

The RTN package is used to reconstruct co-expression networks around the human transcription factors. In that way, each transcription factor will comprise a regulon, that is, a group of genes that are regulated together by a given driver (in this case, a transcription factor).

This step requires a huge amount of memory and processing power. So, it is strongly suggested to be run in a dedicated server.

# Importing TFs list to be used as regulons
tfs <-read.table('DatabaseExtract_v2.0.txt', sep = '\t', quote = '', header = T)
tfs <- tfs[tfs$isTF == 'Yes',]
tfs <- unique(c(tfs$Ensembl.ID))

# Importing normalized gene-level counts from RUV-seq normalized data
cardozo_data <- read.table(file = 'normCounts_RUV.csv', header = T, sep = '\t',
                           row.names = 1)

cardozo_data = vst(as.matrix(cardozo_data))

microglia_exp_matrix <- as.matrix(subset(correctedExpression, rownames(correctedExpression) %in% rownames(cardozo_data)))
microglia_exp_matrix <- subset(microglia_exp_matrix, rownames(microglia_exp_matrix) %in% gene_annot$ENSEMBL)

tfs <- tfs[which(tfs %in% rownames(microglia_exp_matrix))]

microglia_tni <- tni.constructor(expData = microglia_exp_matrix,
                                 regulatoryElements = tfs,
                                 rowAnnotation = gene_annot)

options(cluster = snow::makeCluster(spec = 20, 'SOCK'))

microglia_tni <- tni.permutation(microglia_tni, pValueCutoff = 3e-7)
microglia_tni <- tni.bootstrap(microglia_tni)
microglia_tni <- tni.dpi.filter(microglia_tni, eps = 0.05, minRegulonSize = 15)

stopCluster(getOption("cluster"))

microglia_tni <- tni.gsea2(microglia_tni, minRegulonSize = 15)

Master Regulator Analysis

After network reconstruction, master regulon analysis was carried out as described in the RTN package vignette. Files generated in DEG analysis using EdgeR are also required in this step.

# Retrieve phenotype and hits files created in DEG analysis

phenotype <- readRDS('numeric_named_DEGs.rds')
hits <- readRDS('hits_DEGs.rds')

# MRA for HCP_tnf vs HCP_ns
mra_hthn <- tni2tna.preprocess(object = microglia_tni, phenotype = phenotype$num_deg_hthn,
                               hits = hits$hits_deg_hthn)
mra_hthn <- tna.mra(mra_hthn, minRegulonSize = 15, tfs = tfs)

mra_hthn_res <- tna.get(mra_hthn, what = 'mra', ntop = -1, idkey = 'SYMBOL')
mra_hthn_res <- mra_hthn_res[mra_hthn_res$Adjusted.Pvalue < 0.05,]

mra_hthn_gsea <- tna.gsea2(mra_hthn, minRegulonSize = 15, sizeFilterMethod = 'posORneg', tnet = 'dpi', signature = c('phenotype', 'hits'))
mra_hthn_gsea <- tna.get(mra_hthn_gsea, what = 'gsea2', ntop = -1)
mra_hthn_gsea <- mra_hthn_gsea$differential
mra_hthn_gsea <- subset(mra_hthn_gsea, mra_hthn_gsea$Regulon %in% mra_hthn_res$Regulon)
write.table(mra_hthn_gsea, file = 'mra_vs_HCP_tnf.csv', quote = F, sep = '\t')

# MRA for SCZ_ns vs HCP_ns
mra_snhn <- tni2tna.preprocess(object = microglia_tni, phenotype = phenotype$num_deg_snhn,
                               hits = hits$hits_deg_snhn)

mra_snhn <- tna.mra(mra_snhn, minRegulonSize = 15, tfs = tfs)

mra_snhn_res <- tna.get(mra_snhn, what = 'mra', ntop = -1, idkey = 'SYMBOL')
mra_snhn_res <- mra_snhn_res[mra_snhn_res$Adjusted.Pvalue < 0.05,]

mra_snhn_gsea <- tna.gsea2(mra_snhn, minRegulonSize = 15, sizeFilterMethod = 'posORneg', tnet = 'dpi', signature = c('phenotype', 'hits'))
mra_snhn_gsea <- tna.get(mra_snhn_gsea, what = 'gsea2', ntop = -1)
mra_snhn_gsea <- mra_snhn_gsea$differential
mra_snhn_gsea <- subset(mra_snhn_gsea, mra_snhn_gsea$Regulon %in% mra_snhn_res$Regulon)
write.table(mra_snhn_gsea, file = 'mra_vs_SCZ_ns.csv', quote = F, sep = '\t')

# MRA for SCZ_tnf vs HCP_ns
mra_sthn <- tni2tna.preprocess(object = microglia_tni, phenotype = phenotype$num_deg_sthn,
                               hits = hits$hits_deg_sthn)

mra_sthn <- tna.mra(mra_sthn, minRegulonSize = 15, tfs = tfs)

mra_sthn_res <- tna.get(mra_sthn, what = 'mra', ntop = -1, idkey = 'SYMBOL')
mra_sthn_res <- mra_sthn_res[mra_sthn_res$Adjusted.Pvalue < 0.05,]

mra_sthn_gsea <- tna.gsea2(mra_sthn, minRegulonSize = 15, sizeFilterMethod = 'posORneg', tnet = 'dpi', signature = c('phenotype', 'hits'))
mra_sthn_gsea <- tna.get(mra_sthn_gsea, what = 'gsea2', ntop = -1)
mra_sthn_gsea <- mra_sthn_gsea$differential
mra_sthn_gsea <- subset(mra_sthn_gsea, mra_sthn_gsea$Regulon %in% mra_sthn_res$Regulon)
write.table(mra_sthn_gsea, file = 'mra_vs_SCZ_tnf.csv', quote = F, sep = '\t')

Overlap between genes regulated by each regulon and the WGCNA modules

To carry out this analysis, we imported the genes list from each WGCNA module obtained in our WGCNA analysis and, then, used the tni.overlap.genesets function from the RTN package.

# Filtering only activated or repressed regulons found in each group

hcp_tnf_sig_mra <- mra_hthn_gsea$Regulon[mra_hthn_gsea$Adjusted.Pvalue < 0.1]
scz_tnf_sig_mra <- mra_sthn_gsea$Regulon[mra_sthn_gsea$Adjusted.Pvalue < 0.1]
scz_ns_sig_mra <- mra_snhn_gsea$Regulon[mra_snhn_gsea$Adjusted.Pvalue < 0.1]

sig_mra <- unique(c(hcp_tnf_sig_mra, scz_ns_sig_mra, scz_tnf_sig_mra))

# Importing WGCNA modules and their associated genes

modules <- read.table(file = 'WGCNA_Modules_Gene.txt', header = T, sep = '\t')
modules[is.na(modules)] <- ''
modules <- stack(modules)
modules <- modules %>% relocate(ind, .before = values)
modules <- modules[modules$values != '',]
modules <- deframe(modules)
modules <- split(unname(modules), names(modules))

# Running overlap between regulon target genes and WGCNA modules

modules_overlap <- t(as.matrix(as.data.frame(tni.overlap.genesets(microglia_tni, modules[c('MEantiquewhite2', 'MEbrown', 'MEblueviolet', 'MEdarkolivegreen2', 'MElightgreen', 'MEpalevioletred')], regulatoryElements = sig_mra,
                                                                  minSetSize = 15, method = 'HT', pValueCutoff = 0.05, sizeFilterMethod = 'posORneg'))))

# Preparing data for heatmap plot

modules_cluster <- matrix(data = 0, nrow = 6, ncol = length(sig_mra))
rownames(modules_cluster) <- c('MEantiquewhite2', 'MEbrown', 'MEblueviolet', 'MEdarkolivegreen2', 'MElightgreen', 'MEpalevioletred')
colnames(modules_cluster) <- c(sig_mra)

for (i in 1:ncol(modules_overlap)){
  a_module <- modules_overlap[1,i]
  a_regulon <- modules_overlap[2,i]
  
  modules_cluster[a_module, a_regulon] <- -log10(as.numeric(modules_overlap[9,i]))
}
rm(i, a_module, a_regulon)

matrix_reg_cluster <- data.frame(regulons = colnames(modules_cluster))
matrix_reg_cluster$cluster <- NA
matrix_reg_cluster$cluster[matrix_reg_cluster$regulons %in% setdiff(hcp_tnf_sig_mra, c(mra_snhn_gsea$Regulon, mra_sthn_gsea$Regulon))] <- 'hcp_tnf'
matrix_reg_cluster$cluster[matrix_reg_cluster$regulons %in% setdiff(scz_tnf_sig_mra, c(mra_hthn_gsea$Regulon, mra_snhn_gsea$Regulon))] <- 'scz_tnf'
matrix_reg_cluster$cluster[is.na(matrix_reg_cluster$cluster)] <- 'same'
rownames(matrix_reg_cluster) <- matrix_reg_cluster$regulons
matrix_reg_cluster <- subset(matrix_reg_cluster, select = 2)

col_cluster <- factor(c(matrix_reg_cluster$cluster), levels = c('hcp_tnf', 'same', 'scz_tnf'))

heatmap2modules <- Heatmap(modules_cluster, col = colorRamp2(seq(0,ceiling(max(modules_cluster)),2), hcl_palette = 'Rocket', reverse = T), border = 'grey30',
                           name = '-log10 p-adj', column_split = col_cluster, row_names_centered = F, column_dend_reorder = T,
                           column_names_side = 'top', column_names_centered = F, cluster_rows = F, cluster_columns = F,
                           show_column_dend = F, show_row_dend = F, row_names_side = 'left', row_gap = unit(2, 'mm'), column_gap = unit(2, 'mm'),
                           show_column_names = T, cluster_column_slices = F, cluster_row_slices = F, column_title = NULL, row_title = NULL,
                           row_names_gp = gpar(fontfamily = 'sans', fontsize = 8),
                           width = ncol(modules_cluster) * unit(3, 'mm'), height = nrow(modules_cluster) * unit(3, 'mm'),
                           column_names_gp = gpar(col = c('#0b5394', 'black', '#e50000'), fontfamily = 'sans', fontsize = 6),
                           heatmap_legend_param = list(title = expression(bold('-log'[10]*' (p-adj)')), grid_height = unit(8, 'mm'), grid_width = unit(4, 'mm'), labels_gp = gpar(family = 'sans', fontsize = 8),
                                                       title_gp = gpar(fontfamily = 'sans', fontsize = 10, fontface = 'bold'), at = seq(0,ceiling(max(modules_cluster)),2),
                                                       title_position = 'topleft'))

tiff('Heatmap Overlap WGCNA Modules and Regulons.tiff', units = 'mm', res = 600, width = 280, height = 35, compression = 'lzw')

heatmap2modules

dev.off()

GO terms enrichment for each selected regulon

GO Biological Processes terms enrichment analysis for each selected regulon was carried out using the tni.annotate.regulons function from the RTN package.

GO terms annotations and their cognate genes were retrieved using biomaRt.

# Retrieving GO term annotations using biomaRt
db_homo_s <- useMart(biomart = 'ENSEMBL_MART_ENSEMBL', dataset = 'hsapiens_gene_ensembl')

genes_go_id <- getBM(attributes = c('ensembl_gene_id', 'hgnc_symbol', 'go_id', 'name_1006', 'namespace_1003'),
                     filters = 'ensembl_gene_id', values = gene_annot$ENSEMBL,
                     mart = db_homo_s, uniqueRows = F, useCache = T)

genes_go_id <- subset(genes_go_id, genes_go_id$namespace_1003 == 'biological_process')

# Creating enriched_gene_set function to run GSEA-like enrichment analysis
# on selected regulons

enriched_gene_set <- function(cluster, regulons){
  cluster <- cluster
  cluster <- deframe(cluster)
  
  enriching_sets <- tni.annotate.regulons(microglia_tni, cluster, regulatoryElements = regulons,
                                            minSetSize = 15, sizeFilterMethod = 'posORneg')
  
  return(enriching_sets)
}

regulons_vs_go_terms <- enriched_gene_set(go_terms_human, sort(c('IRF1', 'CENPA', 'MXD3', 'HHEX', 'SOX4', 'MEF2C', 'NFATC2')))
